WEBVTT

01:31.358 --> 01:34.293
[wind whooshing]

01:34.361 --> 01:37.530
[thunder rumbling]

01:41.368 --> 01:42.435
[thunder cracks]

01:42.503 --> 01:45.605
[rain pattering]

01:49.110 --> 01:50.575
[horse neighs]

01:50.577 --> 01:53.578
[dark music]

01:53.580 --> 01:58.183
♪

01:58.252 --> 02:00.052
[gate creaks]

02:00.121 --> 02:07.126
♪

02:19.674 --> 02:23.208
[ominous music]

02:23.278 --> 02:30.149
♪

02:35.556 --> 02:38.357
[woman fussing]

02:38.425 --> 02:45.097
♪

02:57.512 --> 03:00.445
[eerie music]

03:00.515 --> 03:07.653
♪

03:10.992 --> 03:15.261
[babies crying]

03:21.336 --> 03:23.602
[bedpan clatters loudly]

03:23.671 --> 03:25.004
- What is it, what is it?

03:25.072 --> 03:26.471
- Where is my baby?
- What are you on about?

03:26.541 --> 03:28.807
- No, my baby, she's--
- Your baby is fine.

03:28.876 --> 03:30.409
- No, my baby's--
- Now calm down.

03:30.477 --> 03:33.078
[overlapping arguing]

03:33.147 --> 03:34.413
- No, my baby's--
- Now calm down.

03:34.481 --> 03:36.682
She's fine.
- No, no, no, no!

03:36.751 --> 03:38.150
No, no, no, no, no--

03:38.219 --> 03:39.752
- Stop it!
- [screams]

03:39.820 --> 03:41.754
- Stop!
- No!

03:41.822 --> 03:44.957
No, no, no, no!

03:45.026 --> 03:48.561
Dr. Markoe!
Please, where is my baby?

03:48.629 --> 03:50.829
You know I know
what happens here!

03:50.898 --> 03:53.699
I'll call the police!
[screams]

03:53.768 --> 03:54.967
Let me see her!

03:55.036 --> 03:58.170
[babies crying]

03:58.239 --> 03:59.905
♪

03:59.907 --> 04:02.507
No, no! My baby!

04:02.509 --> 04:09.415
♪

04:20.395 --> 04:23.528
[dramatic music]

04:23.530 --> 04:30.369
♪

04:44.952 --> 04:52.124
♪

05:10.645 --> 05:13.646
[tense music]

05:13.714 --> 05:17.850
♪

05:17.918 --> 05:19.652
[men shouting in distance]

05:19.720 --> 05:22.655
[suspenseful music]

05:22.723 --> 05:28.393
♪

05:28.463 --> 05:30.663
- Dr. Kreizler.

05:30.731 --> 05:32.865
Come to free the sinners?

05:32.933 --> 05:35.468
- According to your Bible,
aren't we all sinners?

05:35.536 --> 05:37.136
- In my book,

05:37.204 --> 05:41.073
butchering your own child
is a crime against God and man.

05:41.142 --> 05:42.541
- Despite your polished shoes

05:42.610 --> 05:44.143
and shiny buttons,
deputy warden,

05:44.211 --> 05:46.011
I do not believe your uniform

05:46.013 --> 05:47.880
gives you the right
to pass sentence.

05:47.948 --> 05:49.815
♪

05:49.817 --> 05:51.284
[woman yelps]

05:51.352 --> 05:52.952
- Slow down!

05:53.020 --> 05:55.754
[horse neighs]
- Whoa!

05:55.823 --> 05:57.957
- I'm sorry. Please hurry.
- Watch where you're going!

05:58.025 --> 05:59.892
[whip cracks, horse neighs]

05:59.960 --> 06:07.066
♪

06:08.769 --> 06:11.704
[soft suspenseful music]

06:11.772 --> 06:17.310
♪

06:17.378 --> 06:21.113
- [gasps softly]
I can still find her smell.

06:21.182 --> 06:23.182
♪

06:23.250 --> 06:28.387
It's faint now,
but it's still there.

06:28.455 --> 06:31.857
♪

06:31.859 --> 06:34.927
What are they calling me?

06:34.996 --> 06:38.464
Are they calling me a monster,
Dr. Kreizler?

06:39.400 --> 06:41.467
- You are not a monster,
Martha.

06:43.137 --> 06:46.872
It is the world
that is monstrous.

06:46.874 --> 06:53.980
♪

07:01.756 --> 07:03.756
- Good morning,
Mrs. Schermerhorn.

07:03.824 --> 07:05.824
- I'm here to see Miss Howard

07:05.893 --> 07:08.761
to receive an update
on my case.

07:08.829 --> 07:10.696
- Milly?

07:10.765 --> 07:12.031
Milly!

07:12.099 --> 07:14.767
♪

07:14.835 --> 07:16.435
- What is all the racket?

07:16.503 --> 07:19.438
♪

07:19.506 --> 07:21.707
Quick, Ida.
All hands on deck.

07:21.776 --> 07:23.242
[lively music]

07:23.310 --> 07:25.711
You take the back stairs.

07:25.713 --> 07:28.113
- Milly will lead you through
to Miss Howard,

07:28.115 --> 07:29.514
Mrs. Schmerhorn.

07:29.584 --> 07:31.584
♪

07:31.652 --> 07:32.985
- Thank you, Ida.

07:33.054 --> 07:35.988
♪

07:36.057 --> 07:37.856
Why is Mrs. Schmerhorn
here today?

07:37.925 --> 07:39.725
- She got the dates mixed up.

07:39.727 --> 07:40.993
Milly's asking after her dogs,

07:41.062 --> 07:42.661
trying to keep her occupied.

07:42.730 --> 07:44.797
- Today, of all bloody days?

07:44.865 --> 07:46.131
A woman is to be put
to her death.

07:46.200 --> 07:47.733
We have no time for this.

07:47.735 --> 07:49.402
♪

07:49.470 --> 07:50.535
They look good.

07:50.605 --> 07:52.271
- I feel positively entombed
in here.

07:52.339 --> 07:54.073
- Well, it was
out of order yesterday,

07:54.141 --> 07:55.874
but it was supposed
to be fixed.

07:55.943 --> 07:57.676
- What progress can we report?

07:57.745 --> 08:00.012
- We did a full inventory
of her silverware.

08:00.081 --> 08:01.880
None of the servants
is stealin' from her.

08:01.949 --> 08:03.082
Oh, you got a smudge.

08:03.150 --> 08:05.084
♪

08:05.152 --> 08:07.820
- The elevator's broke again.
She left in a huff.

08:07.888 --> 08:10.623
- Thank God for small mercies.
Milly, get the banners.

08:10.691 --> 08:14.760
♪

08:14.762 --> 08:16.495
- The carriage is ready,
Miss Sara.

08:16.563 --> 08:18.964
- Thank you, Ida.

08:19.033 --> 08:21.166
Delmonico's, please.
- Yes, ma'am.

08:21.235 --> 08:22.901
♪

08:22.970 --> 08:26.371
- Kreizler feels there's
a fair chance of reprieve,

08:26.373 --> 08:29.775
but if we could use
your good graces to--

08:29.844 --> 08:30.910
Y--I understand,

08:30.978 --> 08:35.114
but a woman's life
is at stake, TR.

08:35.182 --> 08:37.516
Whatever you can do.

08:37.584 --> 08:39.918
Thank you, Teddy.

08:39.987 --> 08:41.654
[sighs]

08:42.189 --> 08:44.523
- Talcum is the talk
of the town.

08:44.592 --> 08:47.126
[laughter]

08:47.194 --> 08:49.528
That's your leaving face.

08:49.597 --> 08:50.663
Must you?

08:50.731 --> 08:52.197
- It's an important day, V.

08:52.266 --> 08:53.532
An important story.

08:53.601 --> 08:54.933
- I know.

08:55.002 --> 08:57.402
Your words
will make a difference.

08:57.472 --> 08:59.805
I wish you would work
with my fa--

08:59.807 --> 09:01.807
my godfather.

09:01.809 --> 09:04.510
Your hours would be your own
at the "Journal."

09:05.813 --> 09:08.948
- I think you mean
my hours would be yours.

09:09.016 --> 09:11.616
- You're so adorable.

09:11.618 --> 09:14.487
I hate that you have to leave
me and poor Mrs. Bamm Bamm

09:14.555 --> 09:17.422
all alone when
we're having such fun.

09:17.492 --> 09:19.424
Isn't that right,
Mrs. Bamm Bamm?

09:19.494 --> 09:21.694
[classical music playing]

09:21.762 --> 09:23.896
- I must leave, I'm afraid, V.

09:23.964 --> 09:30.803
♪

09:31.839 --> 09:35.641
Maurice, I realize
there's an outstanding, uh--

09:35.710 --> 09:38.377
but I was hoping
to put the luncheon on my tab.

09:38.445 --> 09:41.914
- Miss Violet asked that
the bill be on her account,

09:41.983 --> 09:44.116
Mr. Moore.

09:44.185 --> 09:45.718
- Oh.

09:45.786 --> 09:46.785
Goodness.

09:46.854 --> 09:48.053
- John, we must hurry.

09:48.122 --> 09:49.788
♪

09:49.857 --> 09:51.190
- Sure, fine.

09:51.258 --> 09:54.727
Okay, well, uh,
thank you, Maurice.

09:54.795 --> 09:57.129
♪

09:57.198 --> 10:00.265
[soft suspenseful music]

10:00.267 --> 10:07.472
♪

10:07.474 --> 10:09.675
Ladies.

10:09.744 --> 10:12.144
- It's somewhat of a tight
squeeze in here, John.

10:12.213 --> 10:13.145
- Yeah.

10:13.214 --> 10:14.479
♪

10:14.549 --> 10:17.149
- Sing Sing Prison!
And hurry, please!

10:17.218 --> 10:23.155
♪

10:23.224 --> 10:26.892
all: Free Martha Napp!
Free Martha Napp!

10:26.961 --> 10:28.561
Free Martha Napp!

10:28.629 --> 10:32.565
Free Martha Napp!
Free Martha Napp!

10:32.633 --> 10:33.632
Free Martha Napp!

10:33.701 --> 10:35.234
- It's a glorious morning,
gentlemen.

10:35.302 --> 10:36.569
- Mr. Byrnes!

10:36.637 --> 10:38.371
In what capacity are you here,
Mr. Byrnes?

10:38.439 --> 10:40.239
- The warden has asked me
to observe

10:40.307 --> 10:42.641
to be sure that these
proceedings are just and fair.

10:42.710 --> 10:45.578
We're demonstrating one
of the new wonders of the age.

10:45.646 --> 10:48.313
The electric chair
is considerably more humane

10:48.383 --> 10:49.648
than death by hanging.
- Mr. Byrnes!

10:49.717 --> 10:51.116
- A fellow won't
shit his pantaloons

10:51.185 --> 10:52.918
in the chair--a woman, neither.

10:52.920 --> 10:57.390
- Brave men do not gather
to murder a woman.

10:57.458 --> 11:01.194
- And what of Elizabeth
Cady Stanton's protests?

11:01.262 --> 11:04.063
- This is not courage.
It's cowardice.

11:04.131 --> 11:08.000
- She was tried
in a court of law.

11:08.069 --> 11:09.402
Fairly tried.

11:09.470 --> 11:13.606
- Where is the body?
This is an outrage!

11:13.674 --> 11:15.274
[protesters shouting
and booing]

11:15.342 --> 11:17.943
all: Justice for Martha!

11:17.945 --> 11:20.145
- We condemn murder!

11:20.214 --> 11:21.814
- Be careful, girls!

11:21.882 --> 11:26.885
- Justice for Martha!
Justice for women!

11:26.954 --> 11:29.822
[protesters cheer]

11:29.891 --> 11:33.759
[indistinct clamoring]

11:33.828 --> 11:35.694
Sara!

11:35.763 --> 11:36.962
Do what you can.

11:37.031 --> 11:40.499
- We will, Elizabeth!
We will!

11:40.567 --> 11:44.036
- Save Martha Napp!
Save Martha Napp!

11:44.105 --> 11:48.107
- Excuse me.
Excuse me.

11:48.175 --> 11:49.909
Press!
- Let him through.

11:51.245 --> 11:53.312
- John Moore, "New York Times."
- Yeah, that's fine.

11:53.380 --> 11:56.181
- Sara Howard,
New York Police Department.

11:56.183 --> 11:57.983
- This is out of date,
Miss Howard.

11:57.985 --> 12:00.253
[tense music]

12:00.321 --> 12:03.522
- My good man,
we just observed Thomas Byrnes,

12:03.591 --> 12:05.057
the former commissioner of
the New York Police Department,

12:05.126 --> 12:06.058
enter through here.

12:06.127 --> 12:07.059
You did not peruse his papers.

12:07.128 --> 12:08.527
- Well, that's Mr. Byrnes,

12:08.595 --> 12:09.595
and I think a former
commissioner deserves--

12:09.664 --> 12:11.063
- I am here from Washington

12:11.132 --> 12:13.332
under the express orders
of Theodore Roosevelt,

12:13.400 --> 12:15.334
the Assistant Secretary
of the Navy,

12:15.402 --> 12:16.802
and reports directly,

12:16.871 --> 12:19.204
directly to the President
of the United States.

12:19.274 --> 12:21.874
♪

12:21.943 --> 12:25.278
So, officer, maybe you want
to think about that and hop to.

12:25.346 --> 12:26.545
♪

12:26.613 --> 12:28.947
- Yes, ma'am--Miss Howard.

12:29.016 --> 12:31.450
[protesters shouting]

12:33.087 --> 12:36.021
- You dissemble with
admirable ease, Miss Howard.

12:36.090 --> 12:38.624
- I have found being able
to tell a small, white lie

12:38.693 --> 12:41.226
on occasion is a most useful
skill, Mr. Moore.

12:41.296 --> 12:44.163
♪

12:44.231 --> 12:47.633
- I don't mind dying,
Dr. Kreizler.

12:47.702 --> 12:49.135
I don't.

12:50.838 --> 12:52.437
But what I do mind

12:52.439 --> 12:55.440
is dying and not knowing
what happened to my baby girl.

12:55.510 --> 12:58.243
[soft dramatic music]

12:58.313 --> 13:00.846
Can I ask you for something?

13:00.915 --> 13:03.248
- Ask anything of me.

13:03.318 --> 13:07.052
- When I'm gone, you find her.

13:07.121 --> 13:10.455
You find my baby girl.

13:10.457 --> 13:12.325
You promise me, Doctor?

13:12.393 --> 13:14.393
♪

13:14.461 --> 13:16.395
- I promise you, Martha.

13:16.463 --> 13:23.536
♪

13:31.812 --> 13:35.748
- They will try to crush us,
but we will not be silenced!

13:35.816 --> 13:37.282
- [snarls]

13:37.284 --> 13:39.018
[shouting, clamoring]

13:39.086 --> 13:40.485
[dog growls]

13:40.555 --> 13:43.956
- [yelps]
- Get off of her!

13:44.025 --> 13:47.492
[tense dramatic music]

13:47.494 --> 13:48.894
- [screaming]

13:48.963 --> 13:52.497
♪

13:52.499 --> 13:55.234
[chains rattling]

13:55.302 --> 14:02.375
♪

14:12.453 --> 14:14.987
- If you find her,
you can give it to her.

14:15.056 --> 14:17.190
♪

14:17.258 --> 14:19.324
[whimpers]

14:19.326 --> 14:23.328
♪

14:23.330 --> 14:25.998
- Roosevelt never called,
did he?

14:26.067 --> 14:27.532
There'll be no reprieve.

14:27.534 --> 14:34.574
♪

14:35.276 --> 14:38.644
[water splashing]

14:41.082 --> 14:42.281
- [whimpers]

14:44.018 --> 14:45.818
- Any last words?

14:49.490 --> 14:52.225
- Stop!

14:52.293 --> 14:53.826
We have to stop this!

14:53.895 --> 14:56.295
- One of the female agitators,
I see.

14:56.363 --> 14:57.562
- This woman is innocent!

14:57.632 --> 14:59.632
This is an outrage,
an abomination!

14:59.700 --> 15:01.300
- I am surprised, Miss Howard,

15:01.368 --> 15:03.702
a lady of your bearing
should be participatin'

15:03.771 --> 15:05.838
in such hooliganism
and lawlessness.

15:05.906 --> 15:07.172
- "A little rebellion
now and then

15:07.241 --> 15:08.841
is a good thing,"
Mr. Byrnes.

15:08.910 --> 15:10.909
- The words of anarchists
and agitators.

15:10.978 --> 15:13.112
- They're the words of
Thomas Jefferson, Mr. Byrnes.

15:13.180 --> 15:14.647
- Officers, please.

15:14.715 --> 15:16.515
Miss Howard is a lady
with a constitutional right

15:16.584 --> 15:17.850
to speak her mind.

15:17.918 --> 15:20.986
- Sara,
we have lost the battle.

15:20.988 --> 15:23.122
♪

15:23.190 --> 15:25.524
- Enough.
- Let go of me!

15:26.127 --> 15:31.464
I ask you all, as you sit here
silently spectating,

15:31.532 --> 15:34.066
where is the body
of the murdered child?

15:34.135 --> 15:35.668
Where?

15:37.404 --> 15:39.272
Shame on you.

15:39.340 --> 15:41.140
Shame on you all.

15:41.208 --> 15:48.381
♪

15:51.886 --> 15:53.486
- [sobbing softly]

15:53.554 --> 15:54.553
[pounds on wall]

15:54.622 --> 15:55.821
♪

15:55.823 --> 15:58.157
[electricity zaps]
[screams]

15:58.225 --> 15:59.692
[chair rattling]

15:59.760 --> 16:02.427
[electricity humming]

16:02.429 --> 16:09.535
♪

16:13.774 --> 16:17.843
- Double it!
2,000 volts!

16:17.845 --> 16:21.180
[electric current crackling]

16:21.248 --> 16:27.052
♪

16:27.121 --> 16:29.121
[crackling stops,
switch clicks]

16:31.526 --> 16:33.626
[loud clang]

16:53.548 --> 16:56.582
[indistinct chatter, shouting]

16:56.651 --> 16:59.752
[horses chuffing]

17:07.595 --> 17:10.863
- Stevie will take you
to "The New York Times."

17:10.931 --> 17:12.398
- Laszlo, wait.

17:15.936 --> 17:18.537
- I have no need
for pity, John.

17:18.539 --> 17:20.006
You should leave.

17:20.074 --> 17:21.139
- I would not be a friend
if I were

17:21.209 --> 17:23.075
to leave you alone like this.

17:23.143 --> 17:24.476
- But there is nothing
you can say that will

17:24.545 --> 17:27.747
make this day seem
any less objectionable.

17:29.684 --> 17:31.884
Martha Napp
put her faith in me.

17:31.952 --> 17:33.552
- And I shall write about her

17:33.621 --> 17:36.955
and all of New York will know
of this injustice.

17:36.957 --> 17:39.091
She will not have died in vain.

17:40.294 --> 17:43.629
- I'm not at all certain that
Martha did not want to die.

17:43.698 --> 17:44.630
- What do you mean?

17:44.699 --> 17:46.032
- She was already dead

17:46.100 --> 17:48.434
before she entered
that execution chamber.

17:48.502 --> 17:51.503
Her only thought
was for her infant child,

17:51.572 --> 17:53.972
and whoever stole that child
killed Martha

17:54.042 --> 17:58.176
as surely as if they had
pulled the lever themselves.

17:58.246 --> 18:01.447
[soft dramatic music]

18:01.515 --> 18:08.421
♪

18:23.871 --> 18:27.006
[ticking]

18:30.144 --> 18:31.177
[distant clattering]

18:34.815 --> 18:38.016
[suspenseful music]

18:38.018 --> 18:45.124
♪

18:47.562 --> 18:49.262
[door clicks, squeaks]

18:54.502 --> 18:57.035
[distant clattering]

18:57.037 --> 19:02.108
♪

19:02.176 --> 19:04.176
[door rattling]

19:04.244 --> 19:06.913
- Put your hands up
and face me.

19:06.981 --> 19:08.581
Stay where you are!

19:08.649 --> 19:10.449
♪

19:10.451 --> 19:12.785
[panting]

19:12.853 --> 19:14.253
I could've shot you.

19:14.322 --> 19:16.589
- You would have been
doing me a service.

19:17.525 --> 19:19.992
I can't seem to get rid
of the smell of burning flesh

19:20.060 --> 19:22.194
out of my nostrils,
which is curious,

19:22.262 --> 19:24.797
because it's no longer
a physical sensation,

19:24.865 --> 19:27.133
but my memory
of what happened today.

19:27.201 --> 19:30.736
- [sighs]
Come in, please.

19:32.140 --> 19:34.006
What would you drink, Laszlo?

19:34.074 --> 19:36.208
- Would have a glass
of burgundy.

19:36.277 --> 19:39.478
- I have American bourbon.
Straight up or watered down?

19:39.547 --> 19:41.814
- [chuckles]

19:41.882 --> 19:43.149
I will have that.

19:43.217 --> 19:46.619
[dog barking in distance]

19:46.687 --> 19:50.623
How goes it with your
brave new adventure, detective?

19:50.691 --> 19:53.425
- Seems that most of my clients
are rich, old dowagers

19:53.494 --> 19:55.894
who think their servants
are stealing from them.

19:55.896 --> 19:57.964
- The curse of the greenback.

19:58.032 --> 19:59.431
The more money they make
during the day,

19:59.500 --> 20:02.068
the more they worry at night
over losing it.

20:05.439 --> 20:08.174
The room
is unquestionably yours, Sara.

20:09.109 --> 20:10.977
- Well, the rent's
not unreasonable,

20:11.045 --> 20:12.444
and we are on Broadway.

20:12.513 --> 20:14.914
- What I meant was--
- I know what you meant.

20:16.184 --> 20:17.449
- You've surrounded yourself

20:17.518 --> 20:19.918
with your most valued
possessions.

20:19.920 --> 20:21.720
And if I were of a mind,

20:21.722 --> 20:23.455
I would tell you much
about who you are

20:23.524 --> 20:27.459
by observing the ephemera
you've chosen to display here.

20:27.528 --> 20:30.596
- It's late, Laszlo.

20:30.665 --> 20:31.998
If you would kindly refrain

20:32.066 --> 20:34.400
from making a psychological
profile of who I am

20:34.468 --> 20:36.836
based on the furnishings
of my office.

20:40.741 --> 20:43.209
- Your father
would be proud of you,

20:43.277 --> 20:45.411
seeing what you have
accomplished.

20:47.348 --> 20:49.182
- I would like to think so.

20:54.822 --> 20:56.055
- Hmm.

20:57.958 --> 21:01.027
It is curious, is it not,

21:01.095 --> 21:02.494
at the time Mary Shelley
was writing this book,

21:02.563 --> 21:05.898
there was a belief
in Galvanism,

21:05.966 --> 21:07.766
that man could
reanimate the body

21:07.768 --> 21:09.635
through the use
of electrical impulses?

21:09.704 --> 21:10.837
And today--

21:10.905 --> 21:12.371
- Today we use
the same potent force

21:12.373 --> 21:15.308
to take the life
of an innocent woman.

21:18.312 --> 21:22.248
- Underneath our skin,
bone, and sinew,

21:22.316 --> 21:24.450
which of us are not monsters?

21:25.653 --> 21:28.987
- It was indeed monstrous
what happened today.

21:28.989 --> 21:31.990
[soft dramatic music]

21:31.992 --> 21:36.795
♪

21:36.797 --> 21:40.866
- I promised her I would look
for her missing child.

21:40.935 --> 21:42.601
♪

21:42.603 --> 21:46.004
- I and my detective agency
are at your disposal.

21:46.006 --> 21:48.941
♪

21:49.009 --> 21:51.143
I'll help you in any way I can.

21:51.211 --> 21:57.215
♪

21:57.217 --> 21:59.217
- I need to first
assess my notes

21:59.287 --> 22:01.087
from my interviews with Martha,

22:01.155 --> 22:05.091
and then I will marshal
all that I know,

22:05.159 --> 22:06.759
all that I've learned,

22:06.827 --> 22:09.695
to determine
what befell the child.

22:09.764 --> 22:12.098
♪

22:12.166 --> 22:14.366
- I can help you, Laszlo.

22:14.435 --> 22:17.503
♪

22:17.572 --> 22:20.038
- Thank you for the bourbon,
Sara.

22:20.040 --> 22:22.040
It was restorative.

22:22.042 --> 22:28.180
♪

22:28.248 --> 22:30.048
And rest assured,

22:30.118 --> 22:34.320
I will call on you
should I need your assistance.

22:34.388 --> 22:39.858
♪

22:39.860 --> 22:42.295
- [exhales deeply]

22:44.264 --> 22:47.333
[indistinct chatter]

22:48.602 --> 22:50.536
- Today's headline,
Martha Napp!

22:50.605 --> 22:53.139
First woman to suffer death
in the electric chair!

22:53.207 --> 22:56.074
[tense music]

22:56.076 --> 22:58.076
- Gentlemen, get your papers.

22:58.146 --> 23:00.947
Papers here!
Mister, your paper?

23:01.015 --> 23:03.882
[indistinct chatter]

23:03.952 --> 23:11.090
♪

23:12.160 --> 23:13.559
- What do you want?

23:13.628 --> 23:15.027
- Thomas Byrnes
is here to see you, Chief.

23:15.095 --> 23:16.228
- Well, send him in, Monckton.

23:16.296 --> 23:17.396
Send him in.

23:20.368 --> 23:23.302
- Mr. Hearst will see you now,
Byrnes.

23:30.178 --> 23:32.845
- Don't stand there, man.
Come in!

23:32.913 --> 23:34.180
- [scoffs]

23:34.248 --> 23:35.581
- Got something on your mind,
Byrnes?

23:35.650 --> 23:40.052
- Well, sir, first off,
I brung you a present.

23:40.120 --> 23:41.988
- What's that?

23:42.056 --> 23:43.422
- It's hair.

23:44.324 --> 23:45.391
But more to the point,

23:45.459 --> 23:47.393
the child murderess
Martha Napp's hair.

23:47.461 --> 23:49.061
- Her hair?
- Yes, sir.

23:49.129 --> 23:50.997
Cut from her scalp
before she met her maker.

23:51.065 --> 23:53.465
I figured you could give it
away in the "Journal."

23:53.534 --> 23:55.401
People have
a morbid fascination

23:55.469 --> 23:58.070
with gruesome memorabilia,
in my experience.

23:58.138 --> 24:00.806
- You leave the running
of the "Journal" to me, Byrnes.

24:00.875 --> 24:02.741
We may not be
"The New York Times,"

24:02.743 --> 24:05.178
but neither are we
PT Barnum's circus.

24:06.547 --> 24:08.814
Besides,
that story's almost over.

24:08.883 --> 24:10.683
We'll remind the American
people of this fact:

24:10.751 --> 24:13.452
She was a murderess
who got her just deserts.

24:16.224 --> 24:18.457
Thank you, Byrnes.
- Thank you, sir.

24:22.830 --> 24:24.864
- Monckton, get in here!

24:26.634 --> 24:28.367
I need one of the brain monkeys
downstairs

24:28.436 --> 24:30.102
to write a new column
for today.

24:30.170 --> 24:32.838
"Spanish spies in New York

24:32.907 --> 24:34.573
bringing their war
to our shores."

24:34.642 --> 24:36.709
You get the picture?
- Of course, Chief.

24:36.777 --> 24:38.110
- That's what the common man
wants to read

24:38.178 --> 24:39.578
over his morning grits.

24:39.647 --> 24:42.248
The United States
standing up to bullies.

24:44.919 --> 24:48.821
[both speaking Spanish]

25:06.941 --> 25:09.876
[soft music]

25:09.944 --> 25:17.149
♪

25:50.250 --> 25:53.319
- [singing softly]

25:56.324 --> 25:59.458
[soft suspenseful music]

25:59.460 --> 26:02.861
♪

26:02.931 --> 26:05.063
- Here you are, ma'am.

26:05.133 --> 26:12.271
♪

26:15.343 --> 26:17.075
- You got a dime, lady?

26:17.077 --> 26:19.946
For a sick soldier--
what served his country good.

26:20.014 --> 26:21.013
Huh?
- Sorry.

26:21.081 --> 26:23.281
[ominous music]

26:23.283 --> 26:25.351
- Spanish whore.

26:25.419 --> 26:31.157
♪

26:31.225 --> 26:32.224
[flash lamp snaps, echoes]

26:32.292 --> 26:33.960
♪

26:34.028 --> 26:35.962
[crow caws]

26:36.030 --> 26:37.295
[horse neighs]

26:37.297 --> 26:40.232
♪

26:40.300 --> 26:42.768
[indistinct whispers]

26:42.837 --> 26:47.239
♪

26:47.307 --> 26:50.977
- [breathing shakily]

26:51.045 --> 26:57.750
♪

27:01.589 --> 27:03.255
[flash lamp snaps, echoes]

27:03.324 --> 27:08.927
♪

27:08.997 --> 27:11.463
[children laughing]

27:11.532 --> 27:14.767
[horses neighing]

27:24.879 --> 27:26.345
[baby fussing]

27:26.347 --> 27:29.448
[shushes gently]

27:39.227 --> 27:42.361
[soft dramatic music]

27:42.363 --> 27:49.468
♪

28:18.132 --> 28:21.067
[unsettling music]

28:21.135 --> 28:28.341
♪

28:43.491 --> 28:46.625
[dissonant suspenseful music]

28:46.627 --> 28:53.733
♪

28:54.903 --> 28:57.036
[gasping]

28:57.838 --> 29:00.540
[screams]

29:06.314 --> 29:09.448
[soft dramatic music]

29:09.517 --> 29:16.422
♪

29:21.929 --> 29:25.131
[telephone ringing]

29:35.409 --> 29:37.877
- Hello?

29:37.945 --> 29:40.612
Yes, Elizabeth, it's me.

29:40.682 --> 29:45.951
♪

29:46.020 --> 29:51.958
- [sobbing and muttering
in Spanish]

29:59.901 --> 30:02.301
- I didn't quite know
what else to do,

30:02.370 --> 30:06.305
who else to call, given
the political sensitivities.

30:06.374 --> 30:09.174
War with Spain seems certain.

30:09.243 --> 30:10.910
- Señora Linares
won't call the police?

30:10.978 --> 30:11.911
- No.

30:11.979 --> 30:13.178
Do you think the police

30:13.247 --> 30:15.047
will want to provide
even one man

30:15.116 --> 30:17.383
to find the daughter
of their enemy?

30:17.451 --> 30:21.253
- This is why we called
upon you, Sara.

30:21.322 --> 30:24.190
- [sighs]
I'm grateful for that trust.

30:25.393 --> 30:27.326
I can assure you,
I will do my utmost

30:27.395 --> 30:29.261
to help you find your daughter.

30:29.263 --> 30:30.862
- Well, yes, Sara.

30:30.932 --> 30:34.934
Isabel and I hoped, we wondered

30:35.002 --> 30:37.069
if we could use
your good graces

30:37.138 --> 30:39.338
to call your friend
Dr. Kreizler?

30:42.410 --> 30:44.676
Dr. Kreizler had some success,
did he not,

30:44.746 --> 30:45.945
with that dreadful monster

30:46.013 --> 30:48.614
who was murdering
young boy prostitutes?

30:49.751 --> 30:51.483
- Indeed, he did.

30:51.552 --> 30:54.554
- And do you not think
his assistance in this case

30:54.622 --> 30:57.223
would be invaluable?

30:58.226 --> 30:59.559
- Should I have a need
for an alienist,

30:59.627 --> 31:01.893
I would not hesitate
to ask Dr. Kreizler

31:01.895 --> 31:04.296
for his help and insight.

31:05.032 --> 31:06.832
But what the Señora requires
now, Elizabeth,

31:06.901 --> 31:10.970
is an expert in the procedural
method of criminal detection,

31:11.038 --> 31:12.972
because there is always
a trail,

31:13.040 --> 31:16.041
no matter the criminal's
stealth or genius.

31:16.844 --> 31:19.445
And if you still hesitate
to consider me professionally,

31:19.513 --> 31:22.248
I will remind you of
the prejudice against our sex

31:22.316 --> 31:25.117
that could impede
this investigation.

31:25.186 --> 31:26.452
Does it not take a woman

31:26.520 --> 31:28.320
to know that a woman
who has lost a child

31:28.389 --> 31:30.656
is neither hysterical
nor irrational,

31:30.724 --> 31:34.460
and that she has cause
to be as she is?

31:34.528 --> 31:37.062
That she must be heard?

31:37.131 --> 31:39.531
You need a detective, Señora,

31:39.533 --> 31:44.103
and a woman such as I with the
resources and the experience.

31:45.739 --> 31:48.340
I see your pain.

31:48.409 --> 31:51.543
I see your suffering.

31:51.545 --> 31:53.745
And I care.

31:53.747 --> 31:55.581
I care, deeply.

31:58.352 --> 32:01.087
- I want you to help me.

32:04.225 --> 32:11.364
♪

32:22.443 --> 32:24.176
- Isabella is sleeping now.

32:24.178 --> 32:28.380
I'm afraid the trauma is
blocking her memory of the day.

32:28.382 --> 32:31.183
- Was the sheet there
when you came in?

32:31.185 --> 32:32.918
- I put it there...

32:32.986 --> 32:35.721
because of this.

32:35.789 --> 32:42.528
♪

32:42.596 --> 32:46.866
- There's something about this
that feels curated,

32:46.934 --> 32:48.734
staged like a work of art.

32:48.802 --> 32:54.273
♪

32:54.342 --> 32:57.543
[indistinct chatter, laughter]

32:59.613 --> 33:00.946
- Order in the court!

33:01.015 --> 33:03.148
- Dr. Markoe
is not an alienist.

33:03.217 --> 33:04.684
He has told the court
nothing about how

33:04.752 --> 33:06.686
Martha Napp's
professed issues in mothering

33:06.754 --> 33:09.755
could have conceivably led
to her murdering her own child.

33:09.823 --> 33:10.890
- Dr. Kreizler--

33:10.958 --> 33:12.424
- I demand justice
for this woman.

33:12.426 --> 33:13.759
I demand justice
for Martha Napp!

33:13.827 --> 33:15.761
- Well, you can demand
all you like,

33:15.829 --> 33:19.298
but this is my courtroom,
and my ruling will stand.

33:19.367 --> 33:22.768
Execution by electric chair.

33:22.836 --> 33:24.503
[gavel pounding]

33:24.572 --> 33:25.971
- Sir?

33:26.574 --> 33:28.407
- I believe I'm done
for the night.

33:30.444 --> 33:33.845
[classical music playing]

33:33.915 --> 33:36.181
♪

33:36.250 --> 33:37.316
- Laszlo.

33:37.385 --> 33:38.850
- Oh, John.

33:38.852 --> 33:41.387
I've been reading a monograph
by Dr. Markoe,

33:41.455 --> 33:43.122
Martha Napp's physician
at the Lying-In Hospital.

33:43.190 --> 33:44.323
- Laszlo, may I--
- He determined

33:44.392 --> 33:46.325
she suffered
from post-term psychosis,

33:46.394 --> 33:49.194
but any symptoms
he describes here--

33:49.263 --> 33:50.662
none of them
were displayed by Martha.

33:50.732 --> 33:51.797
- Laszlo, I--

33:51.865 --> 33:53.199
- His theories
are preposterous,

33:53.267 --> 33:54.866
contradictory, and inane.

33:54.936 --> 33:56.202
- [clears throat]

33:56.270 --> 34:00.606
May I present my fiancée,
Miss Violet Hayward?

34:00.674 --> 34:04.143
- Oh.
Miss Hayward.

34:04.211 --> 34:06.545
- V, this is Dr. Kreizler.

34:06.614 --> 34:10.015
- The famous Dr. Kreizler?
The alienist?

34:10.084 --> 34:13.085
- I hazard that I'm more
derided than acclaimed.

34:13.154 --> 34:16.021
- I fear if I spoke with you
at any great length,

34:16.090 --> 34:18.958
you would know the deep
recesses of my mind.

34:19.026 --> 34:20.660
- Or the shimmering shadows.

34:21.763 --> 34:23.695
- Laszlo.

34:23.697 --> 34:25.798
Sometimes you go too far.

34:27.301 --> 34:29.969
- I thought we were dining
à deux tonight, my darling,

34:30.037 --> 34:32.904
but perhaps
if Dr. Kreizler is joining us,

34:32.906 --> 34:34.106
he should pull up a pew.

34:34.108 --> 34:38.010
- I think Laszlo was--
- Already leaving.

34:38.913 --> 34:41.914
Every mind is like the ocean,
Miss Hayward.

34:41.983 --> 34:44.784
There's surface and depth
in all of us.

34:49.256 --> 34:52.524
- [sighs]

34:52.593 --> 34:55.461
- Good night, my friend.
- Good night.

34:55.529 --> 34:58.530
♪

34:58.532 --> 35:01.533
[soft music]

35:01.535 --> 35:05.471
♪

35:05.539 --> 35:07.473
- Whoever it is could've
conceivably come through

35:07.541 --> 35:08.608
any of these windows.

35:08.676 --> 35:09.809
- The staff swear blind

35:09.877 --> 35:12.077
they had the windows closed
at night.

35:12.146 --> 35:13.545
- Of course they do.

35:13.547 --> 35:15.947
They're afraid
of getting into trouble.

35:15.949 --> 35:17.016
You think in this heat

35:17.084 --> 35:19.551
they're not going to at least
open them for air?

35:19.621 --> 35:22.822
[soft suspenseful music]

35:22.890 --> 35:25.957
♪

35:25.959 --> 35:29.361
They entered here.
The frame's been damaged.

35:29.430 --> 35:36.302
♪

35:39.040 --> 35:40.972
Give me a boost, Bitsy.

35:40.974 --> 35:47.880
♪

36:04.398 --> 36:06.598
- Where does it go?

36:06.668 --> 36:09.268
- Leads to 5th Avenue.

36:09.337 --> 36:11.270
They could be anywhere
in New York.

36:11.339 --> 36:16.409
♪

36:20.514 --> 36:23.449
[suspenseful music]

36:23.517 --> 36:30.322
♪

36:30.391 --> 36:33.526
- Dr. Kreizler,
ain't we wasting our time?

36:34.996 --> 36:38.264
- Time is never wasted
when one is thinking.

36:38.332 --> 36:41.533
That is what is wondrous
about the human mind.

36:41.603 --> 36:43.002
♪

36:43.070 --> 36:46.271
We may appear still,
yet all the time,

36:46.340 --> 36:49.074
in here,
we're conducting symphonies,

36:49.143 --> 36:51.210
solving the most arduous
mathematical problems,

36:51.278 --> 36:54.480
and contemplating the mysteries
of the universe.

36:55.082 --> 36:57.683
- Doing all those things
right now, Doctor?

36:59.553 --> 37:00.686
- No, Stevie.

37:00.754 --> 37:04.156
[dark music]

37:04.225 --> 37:10.429
♪

37:10.498 --> 37:11.631
- Dr. Markoe--

37:11.699 --> 37:13.765
- One moment,
if you please, Matron.

37:13.835 --> 37:15.767
Count to ten and then tell me.

37:15.837 --> 37:20.906
♪

37:20.974 --> 37:22.174
- Dr. Kreizler is outside.

37:22.243 --> 37:24.176
He gave me his card
to give to you.

37:24.178 --> 37:26.378
- Do not be alarmed, Matron.

37:26.380 --> 37:27.913
We run a tight ship here,

37:27.981 --> 37:30.982
and we do that by discipline,
order, and example.

37:30.984 --> 37:33.985
An example needed to be set
with Martha Napp.

37:33.987 --> 37:35.521
- What will I tell him?

37:35.589 --> 37:38.590
- Simply tell him
I'm indisposed.

37:38.660 --> 37:41.460
On second thoughts,

37:41.529 --> 37:44.030
tell him to go to hell.

37:47.735 --> 37:49.268
- I went to the hospital
and the morgue

37:49.337 --> 37:51.537
like you asked, Miss Sara,
but we got nothing.

37:51.605 --> 37:55.741
All babies accounted for except
for one, but it was a him.

37:55.809 --> 37:57.409
Poor little thing.

37:57.411 --> 37:59.879
His head was swoll up
the size of a cantaloupe.

37:59.947 --> 38:01.146
- It's difficult the first time

38:01.215 --> 38:03.815
you're confronted
with death, Milly,

38:03.817 --> 38:05.818
especially
when they're so young.

38:07.088 --> 38:09.221
Bitsy, will you take a message
to John Moore?

38:09.223 --> 38:11.023
Ask him if there's been
any developments

38:11.025 --> 38:12.558
in the Martha Napp story.

38:12.626 --> 38:14.426
There may be a connection.

38:14.495 --> 38:16.896
Just tell them to call
if he hears anything.

38:18.299 --> 38:20.966
This is a real case.

38:21.035 --> 38:23.168
None of our previous endeavors
made a difference,

38:23.237 --> 38:24.836
but this one does.

38:24.838 --> 38:26.906
It's life and death, girls.

38:28.910 --> 38:31.711
[distant rumbling]

38:31.779 --> 38:34.714
[bell ringing]

38:34.782 --> 38:37.984
[indistinct chatter]

38:42.790 --> 38:45.892
[train rumbling]

38:47.461 --> 38:48.928
- If you're a good girl,

38:48.996 --> 38:52.532
Nanny will get you a 5¢ soda
cream from the fountain after.

38:52.600 --> 38:53.966
Can you do that?

38:56.938 --> 38:59.871
[soft dramatic music]

38:59.941 --> 39:07.079
♪

39:08.816 --> 39:10.082
[chimes ring]

39:10.151 --> 39:13.286
[music box playing]

39:17.158 --> 39:18.490
- Good day, sir.
- Good morning.

39:18.559 --> 39:20.760
Welcome to Siegel-Cooper.

39:20.828 --> 39:23.763
- Not too far, Eloise.

39:23.831 --> 39:26.766
[dramatic music]

39:26.834 --> 39:33.973
♪

39:44.118 --> 39:47.386
[eerie ominous music]

39:47.455 --> 39:54.460
♪

40:06.940 --> 40:14.013
♪

40:16.484 --> 40:19.952
- [screaming]

40:20.021 --> 40:23.389
[telephone ringing]

40:24.358 --> 40:26.292
- Good morning,
"New York Times."

40:26.360 --> 40:29.361
- This Martha Napp article's
not bad at all, John.

40:29.430 --> 40:31.563
It's not up there with
Hawthorne, but it's not bad.

40:31.633 --> 40:34.166
Are you sure you don't want
to go back to the society pages

40:34.168 --> 40:36.969
with your--
- My own kind?

40:37.038 --> 40:38.437
I think I've got quite used to

40:38.506 --> 40:40.572
looking at your ugly mug
every day, Bernie.

40:40.574 --> 40:42.842
- Mm, don't know
if I'm gonna run with it yet.

40:42.910 --> 40:45.444
There's a lot of big
statements here, John.

40:45.513 --> 40:48.147
It's gonna make a lot
of important folks angry.

40:50.051 --> 40:53.052
- Did I mention that I'm angry?

40:53.120 --> 40:56.722
What kind of world do we
live in for this to happen?

40:56.790 --> 40:58.457
The blood of innocents
was spilt.

40:58.526 --> 41:01.126
[telephone ringing]

41:01.195 --> 41:02.995
- "New York Times."
Hello?

41:02.997 --> 41:04.396
- Bernie, wait up.
- Yeah?

41:04.398 --> 41:06.332
- Walk with me, John.
- Yeah?

41:06.400 --> 41:08.267
- Every other newspaper
is saying

41:08.336 --> 41:10.069
that she did away
with her child.

41:10.137 --> 41:11.871
I appreciate your ardor,

41:11.939 --> 41:13.605
but to run a story,
we need facts.

41:13.607 --> 41:15.140
We got any new ones?
- Bernie, hear me out.

41:15.209 --> 41:16.742
- I got a lunch at McSorley's
with someone

41:16.810 --> 41:18.610
from Boss Croker's finance
committee in five minutes.

41:18.612 --> 41:20.212
- Boss, boss!

41:20.214 --> 41:21.681
- Who knows,
you give me some facts,

41:21.749 --> 41:22.682
maybe we can come back to it.

41:22.750 --> 41:24.884
- Boss!
- Maude.

41:24.952 --> 41:27.152
- I've been calling you.
This just in.

41:27.221 --> 41:29.288
They found a dead baby's body
down at Siegel-Cooper.

41:29.357 --> 41:31.090
- When was this, Maude?
- Late morning.

41:31.158 --> 41:32.892
Cops haven't even
confirmed it yet.

41:32.960 --> 41:35.027
- See where it leads,
but go easy.

41:35.096 --> 41:37.029
- Thank you.

41:37.031 --> 41:38.497
Maude, I need you to ensure

41:38.566 --> 41:39.765
Miss Howard
gets there directly.

41:39.833 --> 41:42.034
Tell her what's happened.

41:42.103 --> 41:43.870
♪

41:48.542 --> 41:50.009
[indistinct chatter]

41:50.077 --> 41:51.143
[flash lamp snaps, sizzles]

41:51.145 --> 41:53.579
[laughter]

41:55.617 --> 41:58.484
- So what are we looking at,
geniuses?

41:58.552 --> 42:00.820
- There's toxic abrasion
in the mouth.

42:02.556 --> 42:04.290
- Burning.

42:04.358 --> 42:06.758
- Yeah, I know what toxic...

42:06.760 --> 42:09.228
- [chuckles]
Abrasion.

42:09.297 --> 42:11.430
- Yeah, I know what it is.

42:11.499 --> 42:15.167
- Burning.
Of the mouth.

42:16.037 --> 42:19.305
- I know I should've also
perhaps sent word for Laszlo,

42:19.373 --> 42:20.840
but it's mere conjecture
at this stage

42:20.908 --> 42:23.643
as to whether
it's the Napp baby or not.

42:23.711 --> 42:25.977
- I fear this is another
missing infant.

42:25.979 --> 42:27.513
- Another?

42:27.581 --> 42:28.848
- I've been asked in confidence

42:28.916 --> 42:30.316
to find the missing
infant daughter

42:30.384 --> 42:32.451
of Spanish Governor-General
Narciso Linares.

42:32.520 --> 42:34.520
- How long has the child
been missing?

42:34.588 --> 42:36.588
- Not long.
Since last night.

42:36.590 --> 42:38.658
I promised the mother
I would find the baby.

42:38.726 --> 42:40.993
- But Sara, you cannot assume
it's the same--

42:40.995 --> 42:43.529
- There was a bloody doll found
in the baby's crib.

42:43.597 --> 42:46.598
It was left there,
presented like a trophy.

42:46.668 --> 42:49.401
The doll was from
Siegel-Cooper.

42:49.403 --> 42:51.803
I fear this is that child,
John.

42:51.805 --> 42:54.340
[soft dramatic music]

42:54.408 --> 42:56.676
- Excuse me, excuse me,
excuse me.

42:56.744 --> 42:58.344
- Run along, now.
- Stand back.

42:58.412 --> 42:59.345
Stand back.

42:59.413 --> 43:02.281
♪

43:02.350 --> 43:04.283
- Marcus!
Lucius!

43:04.352 --> 43:07.152
- Sara.
It's okay.

43:07.221 --> 43:10.890
♪

43:10.958 --> 43:13.092
- What can you tell me
about the child?

43:15.029 --> 43:16.628
- Girl or boy?

43:16.630 --> 43:17.629
- It's a girl.

43:17.631 --> 43:19.365
- How long is she dead?

43:19.433 --> 43:21.166
- The child had died
quite recently.

43:21.235 --> 43:22.368
It's hard to say for sure.

43:22.436 --> 43:24.236
- Oh, no.

43:24.305 --> 43:26.806
Would it be possible for me
to have a look at the baby?

43:28.109 --> 43:29.841
Please,
it would mean a great deal.

43:29.843 --> 43:31.844
- We just saw Doyle
and his men leaving.

43:33.114 --> 43:35.915
- He'll be back any minute.
- We'll be quick.

43:35.983 --> 43:42.955
♪

43:47.194 --> 43:49.595
- What is it, Sara?
- It's nothing.

43:49.663 --> 43:55.000
♪

43:55.069 --> 43:58.203
Oh, dear God.

43:58.272 --> 44:01.273
- Is it the Spanish child?

44:01.275 --> 44:04.410
- It has similar markings on
its eyes to that of the doll,

44:04.478 --> 44:07.947
but I don't believe so.

44:08.015 --> 44:09.081
Is that blood?

44:09.150 --> 44:10.282
- Congealed blood, yes,

44:10.351 --> 44:12.217
but perhaps some other matter.

44:12.286 --> 44:15.755
What we hypothesize
was a toxic causality.

44:15.823 --> 44:18.758
- What my brother means
is we guess poison.

44:19.561 --> 44:21.627
- How do you guess poison?

44:21.695 --> 44:24.029
- There are lesions,
burns inside the mouth

44:24.098 --> 44:26.732
consistent with that type
of material.

44:28.636 --> 44:30.670
- And the child
was found where?

44:32.373 --> 44:34.706
- Here.

44:34.708 --> 44:36.508
A girl was in the shop.

44:36.510 --> 44:38.177
She picked it up
thinking it was a doll.

44:38.245 --> 44:45.184
♪

44:45.252 --> 44:46.586
- I think it would be useful

44:46.654 --> 44:48.387
to have Laszlo
come and take a look.

44:48.456 --> 44:50.122
- I can't have you here, Sara.

44:50.191 --> 44:52.257
I certainly
can't have Laszlo here.

44:52.326 --> 44:53.693
- Well, if not now, when?

44:55.997 --> 44:58.264
- We will send him a message
to meet us at the lab.

44:58.332 --> 45:05.505
♪

45:11.679 --> 45:13.713
[flash lamp snaps, sizzles]

45:16.484 --> 45:18.950
- The child was poisoned,
you said?

45:18.952 --> 45:20.620
- Yes.

45:20.688 --> 45:24.690
- Have you identified her?
- No. How could we?

45:24.758 --> 45:28.561
- Martha mentioned her child
had an identifying contusion.

45:29.763 --> 45:31.097
May I?

45:33.034 --> 45:36.435
A benign hemangioma
under her left axilla.

45:36.504 --> 45:43.609
♪

45:48.716 --> 45:50.782
It's what I feared.

45:50.784 --> 45:57.890
♪

46:00.061 --> 46:03.729
- So the dead child
is Martha Napp's?

46:03.797 --> 46:09.268
♪

46:09.337 --> 46:11.671
- These are the photographs
Marcus took of the Napp child

46:11.739 --> 46:13.739
at Siegel-Cooper,

46:13.807 --> 46:15.607
and these are from the autopsy.

46:15.609 --> 46:17.943
♪

46:18.012 --> 46:21.213
The markings on the eyes
are so curious.

46:21.215 --> 46:24.816
- It reminds me of--
- Posthumous portraiture.

46:24.818 --> 46:28.420
- Memento mori.
Remembrances of death.

46:28.422 --> 46:31.891
- Grieving parents
had the eyes painted on plates

46:31.959 --> 46:35.627
to give the illusion
the child is still alive.

46:35.629 --> 46:37.429
- Do you think someone
is grieving

46:37.431 --> 46:38.698
for the child they have killed?

46:38.766 --> 46:41.433
- Grief can be tangled,
impenetrable,

46:41.502 --> 46:43.969
elaborate, and tortuous.

46:44.038 --> 46:46.972
- It doesn't feel like grief,
though.

46:47.041 --> 46:49.241
It feels like a Pandora's box
of emotions,

46:49.243 --> 46:51.777
someone who is unmanned
and untethered.

46:51.845 --> 46:54.313
It feels diabolical.

46:54.382 --> 46:58.183
- The doll is a repository
of the evil within.

46:58.252 --> 46:59.451
It allows the killer

46:59.453 --> 47:01.520
to dissociate
from the cruelty of the act.

47:01.589 --> 47:04.056
It allows the killer to--
- To love.

47:05.459 --> 47:08.327
It allows the killer to love.

47:08.396 --> 47:15.601
♪

47:16.804 --> 47:19.739
Who could've done this?

47:19.807 --> 47:23.475
- A person in great pain,

47:23.477 --> 47:28.214
retreated into themselves,
alone in their desolation.

47:28.282 --> 47:32.551
Presenting to the world a face
to mask their own darkness.

47:32.620 --> 47:34.553
[soft dissonant music]

47:34.622 --> 47:39.224
[baby crying]

47:39.293 --> 47:42.227
- Baby Ana is at their mercy.

47:42.296 --> 47:44.430
♪

47:44.498 --> 47:48.500
- Well, whoever they are,
they will kill again.

47:48.569 --> 47:53.840
[baby crying]

47:54.442 --> 47:56.843
- We must begin.
